question:
As reported in Section III, migration energies were explicitly calculated for various defects, specifically for negatively and positively charged hydrogen vacancies (
V_{m H}^{-}
 and 
V_{m H}^{+}
), interstitial hydrogen (
H	extsubscript{i}^{-}
), negatively charged sodium vacancies (
V_{m Na}^{-}
), positively charged sodium interstitial (
Na	extsubscript{i}^{+}
), positively charged aluminum hydride vacancies (
V_{m AlH_{4}}^{+}
), and interstitial molecular hydrogen ((H	extsubscript{2})	extsubscript{i}
). Explicit calculations for migration paths proved cumbersome for other defects, including positively charged interstitial hydrogen (
H	extsubscript{i}^{+}
), sodium hydride vacancies (
V_{m NaH}
), aluminum hydride vacancies (
V_{m AlH_{3}}
), positively charged aluminum vacancies (
V_{m Al}^{+}
), and negatively charged aluminum vacancies (
V_{m Al}^{-}
). These complexities arise because these defects can be considered complexes of more elementary native point defects. However, one can estimate a lower bound for their migration energies by considering the higher of the migration barriers of the constituent defects. For example, 
H	extsubscript{i}^{+}
 can be viewed as a complex of 
V_{m H}^{+}
 and (H	extsubscript{2})	extsubscript{i}
, suggesting a minimum migration barrier of 0.26 eV, the value for 
V_{m H}^{+}
. This estimate is considered a lower limit as it assumes the complex remains fully bound during migration. Should partial breaking occur, additional energy would be required, thereby increasing the barrier value. Similarly, migration barriers for other defects regarded as complexes were determined. Aluminum-related vacancies, for example, were considered combinations of 
V_{m AlH_{4}}^{+}
, (H	extsubscript{2})	extsubscript{i}
, and 
H	extsubscript{i}^{-}
. The sodium hydride vacancy (
V_{m NaH}
) was regarded as a combination of 
V_{m Na}^{-}
 and 
V_{m H}^{+}
.
